Ippudo is my favorite Japanese  ramen noodle brassiere in New York. There are about 43 Ippudo restaurants in Japan and NYC is Ippudo's first location overseas. Located in the East Village, Ippudo is always bustling with New Yorkers anxiously waiting to experience authentic Japanese ramen. Ippudo's 4,000 rave reviews on Yelp and a 26 out of 30 Zagat review doesn't help with peak hour wait times, but a 20-30 minute wait for dinner is well worth it. The foundation of ramen is a basic broth, based from either pork, chicken, beef, or seafood, then seasoned with soy sauce, miso, and lots of other delicious ingredients.  The noodles at Ippudo are homemade and hand-pulled. My favorite ramen at Ippudo is the Akamaru Modern which is the original "Tonkotsu" (pork) soup noodles, topped with Ippudo's secret "Umami Dama" miso paste, pork , cabbage, sesame mushrooms, scallions, and fragrant garlic oil. Comforting, delicious and joyously slurp-able! Perfect for a cold New York night. The chicken wings are a fantastic and surprisingly delicious appetizer. They are fried and glazed with a black pepper sauce and topped with black and white sesame seeds.  Crispy, spicy and sweet, with a wonderful earthy flavor from the sesame seeds. Ippudo also offers traditional Japanese appetizers ranging from edamame to sashimi.
