d was the neat presentation. For something that's about to get mixed and stirred, they take the time to present it well, and I appreciated that, for about 3 seconds. The sliced pork is fanned out, as are the other veggies and ingredients. The scoop of miso paste is right in the middle. So, just like most ramens are, it's salty, but not uncomfortably salty. Think French Onion soup salty. The noodles are like spaghetti noodles, but 1/2 the thickness. The pork is very moist, and a bit fatty. The health nut would probably discard the fat, but I definitely ate it, with a lot of guilt, mind you. It was so buttery and flavorful, but my mouth felt like Crisco after eating it. The pork (non add-on) was sort of like in big golf ball size chunks, and you had to sort of pull it apart or bite off pieces. It wasn't anywhere near as tender as the pork belly (paid addon), but it tasted fine, and provided protein so I was happy. The soup base (which is why we're here, right?) was delicious, but with a catch. I definitely tasted miso and garlic, something subtly sweet, and extremely small amounts of ginger (which is the way I like it). Very good. The saltiness, and I know it's part of the "Ramen Experience," would sort of go in and out of favor with me with each slurp. Slurp1, it's amazing! Slurp2, whoa a little salty, Slurp3, same, drink water, Slurp4, amazing! So, all in all, a satisfying meal, albeit freaking $21 after my addons, before tax/tip! It had the volume (if you drink the soup like I did), and with the addons, a good helping of protein. You won't get to "Ugh! I'm never eating again!" full, but you'll be at that perfect satiety afterwards. NARUTO WOULD PROBABLY BE ECSTATIC! ...but I just thought it was pretty good. I'm not that big of a ramen fan. I love soups and stews, so I can imagine myself having a craving for ramen occasionally, but not for anything specific to Ippudo. Also, more often than not, I'll probably opt for Pho instead...or Korean ramyun if I'm too lazy to 