There are so many real Japanese people here. We got to Ippudo at 2:30, an hour before they close for lunch. At first, we were told that they weren't taking any more names, but I asked if they had a stand by list or anything, in case people left before their names were called. We totally lucked out, because within 20 minutes, we got a text saying to go to the hostess within 5 minutes. Well, I didn't actually think we'd be able to get in, so we were a little delayed going back. I texted, "on our way back." at 3. When we did get back, around 3:10, we were seated promptly. When you walk into the dining area, the hostess announces your arrival in Japanese, and you're greeted by the staff. I've heard about the communal dining tables, and I was expecting to sit elbow to elbow with the person next to you, like you would at a picnic table at a crowded festival. To my relief, it was better than that; we sat at a long table surrounding a charcoal centerpiece and sat on chairs, not a bench. Ippudo must be written up in lots of Japanese magazines about NYC, because to our left and right were couples from Japan. I'm not sure what they thought of the ramen, but here's my take: I had the Shiromaru Hakata Classic lunch special with mentaiko over rice, and salad. The ramen was good. The noodles had koshi, and even when I finished, they weren't soggy. Aren't soggy noodles the worst? The broth is delicious. It's not too salty or heavy, and I didn't feel sick or excessively thirsty after eating it. The nitamago ($2) is really hanjyuku, soft-boiled, and the menma (bamboo) is thick. Does Ippudo make their menma in-house? It's thicker and cut more irregularly than menma at other places, and otherwise, why would it be $4 for extra? Salad had a sesame shoyu dressing. It was good, but you don't go to Ippudo to eat salad. What I liked most was the mentaiko over rice. Maybe it's because mentaiko is $12 at Sunrise Mart, and I was thrilled that I could have mentaiko over rice for only $3 extra. Rice with cabbage, seaweed, some kewpie mayonnaise, and mentaiko. I could eat it every day. If you're from the Bay Area or Southern CA, you'll leave Ippudo thinking your local ramen places are just as good. Maybe Ippudo's broth is a little better, and their noodles are slightly thinner, but when you factor the wait and price difference, maybe it all evens out. On the menu, there's a ramen called Kogashi Karaka Miso Ramen, spicy miso ramen. The whole time I was at Ippudo, I kept thinking about how odd it was that the word "karaka" was used on the menu. "Karaka" is the word "spicy" in the Kagoshima dialect. Seeing as how the founder of Ippudo, Kawahara Shigemi, is from Fukuoka, I guess now it makes sense; Fukuoka is in northern Kyushu, and Kagoshima is in southern Kyushu. While the dialects aren't exactly the same, I can't help but assume that's where the word comes from. And, for that, Ippudo earns a fifth star. Kagoshima-ben for all!
