Ippudo is epic, as are the waits to eat here and the food coma you'll experience afterwards. While their ramen is really, really good and deliciously excellent, there are a few other places in the city that do ramen just as good or come close to what Ippudo does. Ok, so why the 5-star rating? Ippudo has some amazing appetizers and small plates, such as the fried chicken, steamed pork buns and spare ribs. All of this can be yours too, so long as you don't mind waiting. My girlfriend and I have been here a few times and the shortest we've ever waited was 45 minutes on a Saturday afternoon. The other two times were 1.5 hours on a Thursday night (around 9:30, nonetheless) around 2 hours on a Saturday afternoon, around 1. The staff says there is always a wait, so all you can do is try your luck and see how long your wait is. Ok, onto the food. On my most recent trip, which was this past Saturday, we started off with the Pork Buns and while we usually get the Fried Chicken, decided to opt for the Spare Ribs this time. We did not regret making the switch from the fried chicken to the spare ribs. The meat was amazingly tender and truly fell right off the bone. Whatever kind of a sauce they put on the ribs was a home run. They also included some chili powder on the side, as well as some kind of a citrus dipping sauce, but the ribs needed neither. The spare ribs served here are far superior to the pork ribs served at the famed Williamsburg BBQ joint, Fette Sau. Regarding the Pork Buns, they are a must for anyone eating here. To describe their taste is difficult - smooth, fluffy and dougy buns with tender, meaty pork, crispy lettuce and some kind of secret sauce. It's the kind of food you dream about. We order them every time, but since Ippudo does not allow take out, I had to satisfy my most recent craving from the Momofuku Ssäm Bar :( Moving onto the ramen, I had the Shiromaru Hakata Classic, which is described as the original silky "Tonkotsu" (pork) soup noodles topped with pork loin chashu, sesame kikurage mushrooms, memma, red pickled ginger, & scallions. My girlfriend had the Akamaru Modern, described as the original silky "Tonkotsu" (pork) soup noodles topped with Ippudo's secret "Umami Dama" miso paste, pork chashu, cabage, sesame kikurage mushrooms, scallions, and fragrant garlic oil. I had originally wanted to get the Modern ramen, but my girlfriend wanted it, so I opted to get something else, so we wouldn't both have the same thing. While both above bowls of ramen were excellent, the broth of the Modern ramen was much superior to that of the Classic ramen. After tasting the broth of the Modern, the Classic almost tasted bland. I'd definitely recommend the Modern ramen over the Classic. Since Ippudo ramen only comes with the pork loin, I opted to add pork belly to my soup, as well as a soft boiled egg. The pork belly is an extra $4 and may seem like a lot, especially when other ramen joints, such as Momofuku or Donburiya include pork belly as a standard, but $4 for pork belly at Ippudo is well spent. You get a heck of a lot of pork belly and they leave the standard pork loin in the soup as well, turning it into a pseudo meat lovers ramen. The soft boiled egg was $2 and perhaps a bit steep for just one egg, but added to the deliciousness of the soup. The egg yolk added a small amount of creaminess. Needless to say that after pork buns, spare ribs and a huge bowl of ramen, I've been so stuffed that I've never tried the desserts, all of which aremade in house - except for the ice creams and sorbets, which are Ciao Bella, and the mille layer crepe cake, which comes from a nearby Japanese bakery. If you don't feel like waiting for 2 hours, there are a few other options nearby, with some being better than others, including Rai Rai Ken, Ramen Setagaya, Minca Ramen Factory and Momofuku Noodle Bar. If you want to head uptown a bit, there's Totto Ramen (where the waits can be long as well) and Donbiuriya. Compared to those other places, Ippudo is definitely on the pricier side. In terms of the portion size, some places give slightly larger portions, while others are on par. Ippudo is a place that everyone needs to experience at least once. Hopefully you'll like it enough to return again and again. And remember, there are only two things you can do after a meal at Ippudo - take a long walk or a long nap :)
