"Where are you? Are you still at the office?" 6:35 p.m. on a Wednesday. A call from my soon-to-be dining companion. "They have a table for us right now." I was still at the office. My tardiness caused us to miss a crucial window, and we wound up spending a half hour in Ippudo's front room, which is designed to handle large crowds waiting endlessly for a chance at ramen. There's a tiny bar stationed opposite the main entrance, staffed by one incredibly busy but rather friendly bartender. Arrive by 7 p.m. and it's happy hour, which means buy a drink and the second round is free. That's great for those with time to spare, but usually I enjoy multiple rounds at the table, not while gazing at the restaurant's display of vintage noodle bowls. We were escorted to a pair of chairs as I was finishing my first beer, in the far back corner of the main dining room. Ippudo has a dark, modernist flair dominated by a support pole covered in bamboo wood that scatters when it hits the ceiling like a series of co-axial cables. We were not placed at the main table - a sushi bar of sorts where chefs prepare fresh bowls of noodles - but at a 10-top split between three different parties. (Oddly, despite the growing crowd waiting in the front room, three chairs remained open the entire meal.) We started with the pork buns, which managed to both be overly complicated and bland. Sitting between the pieces of sliced meat and the squishy bun were pieces of lettuce and a chili aioli. The lettuce reminded me of cheap midtown sushi restaurants that use it to pad out budget rolls, while the aioli wasn't spicy enough. For $8, we each received a couple of bites and these buns didn't distinguish themselves to justify that price point. For the main course, I went for the Akamaru Modern (per the menu -  "the original tonkotsu soup noodle with ippudo's special sauce, pork belly chashu, cabbage, kikurage, scallions, miso paste & fragrant garlic oil") while my friend settled on a more traditional tonkotsu or pork bone broth. Amazingly, my bowl of noodles managed to lack much of any taste, even with the laundry list of ingredients I just listed. Cho's tasted a bit better, with a stronger miso taste and the richness of the pork bone coming through. Ippudo is a strange animal. It's a high-volume, high-turnover place, a restaurant where waiters and busboys are lunging at half-eaten dishes, attempting to clear entrees five minutes after they are served. But it also tries to represent itself as a classy eating establishment, with quality ingredients and preparations, even though diners have to hang out for hours with hundreds of college students before entering. Pass.
