I arrived at Ippudo rather late in the evening, having had a (sushi) dinner earlier that night, so I wasn't terribly hungry. I love having a bowl of noodles (ramen, udon, etc.) before going to sleep, yea I know about carbs before bed. I wouldn't consider Ippudo a dedicated Ramen-Ya, it's has almost a full restaurant menu, sadly gyoza isn't included in their extensive offerings. I've heard that the wait times at Ippudo can be legendary, I was alone and fortunately got seated immediately at what seemed to be a large communal table. The waitress told me about their special of "Kuro Tan Tan Men", I was easily sold. This classic Szechuan dish served at Ippudo had a slightly different and progressive interpretation from this old stand by. Instead of that almost orangish color caused by the use of Ji-Ma Jan (goma) sesame paste, Ippudo uses a kuro goma (black sesame) sauce which gives it a dark, almost blackish/red rich broth. Instead of chili oil, shrimp oil is used with cilantro and lime, an innovative twist, but the dish still remains true to form. With the additional side of Bukadan (spicy paste) and a Sapporo Draft, what's not to like. Another thing that sets Ippudo apart from others is that I didn't notice ( I was somewhat inebriated and wasn't really looking either) one Japanese employee while there. Usually that's a complete deal breaker amongst Japanese people, but most of my J-Yelp friends give this place a resounding 4 or 5 stars, and at my communal table were several parties of Japanese nationals happily slurping away. It's just in America, Japanese (especially the guys!!) people just don't slurp as loud as they do when they are at home, in Japan!!
