Well, Ippudo has more than 3,000 awesome reviews but I'm gonna have to write another one. I arrived at 5:40 on a Tuesday evening, and expected a terrifying wait. "How long is the wait for a party of three?" I asked. WE HAVE A TABLE RIGHT NOW, they responded. I was quite shocked, but unfortunately they (obviously) couldn't seat me until my full party arrived. My two friends got there a few minutes after 6, and there was a bit of a wait by then. However, we were seated by 6:30. Not bad, Ippudo, considering I was expecting to have to wait until 9pm or something. That being said, it would have been worth the wait. Order a Sapporo, it'll go well with your ramen. Then, order the pork buns. They are something like $9/order, and only two buns per order, but they are so worth it. The bun is fluffy like a cloud and perfectly chewy, honestly this dough surrounding the flavorful, juicy marinated pork belly, combined with crunchy lettuce and spicy mayo- seriously a sensual experience.  Yes. Sensual pork buns. As for ramen, they all run about $15 and there are maybe 8 to choose from. There was a special (Szechuan ramen, very spicy apparently) that also looked great. I ordered the Modern, as did another one of my friends, and then the third in our party ordered the Classic. These two were mentioned in so many yelp reviews, food critic reviews, etc, that we just decided to stick to them and not branch out. Maybe next time! The Modern ramen was AMAZING. First of all, the broth was ridiculously complex, almost creamy (?!?!). This dish was chock full of umami. I have no idea what was in it to make it this way, but I couldn't stop slurping spoonfuls of the broth by itself. Usually I find ramen broth to be mostly just salt-flavored, but this was nothing like that. (sidenote: it was really salty and I am still parched/thirsty from the meal last night but it didn't really matter because it was so not the overwhelming flavor here.) The broth was also really porky and fatty, but in the best way possible. There's a distinct possibility that my previous sentence sounds disgusting, but I promise the porky/fattiness was a good thing. It was HEARTY broth. Anyway, they recommended adding a soft-boiled egg or pork belly to the Modern ramen but I opted just to get it with its standard ingredients (including scallions, mushrooms, pork belly, ground pork, and cabbage- I think). The additions probably would have been awesome (although pork belly could have been redundant since it comes with a bit of pork belly anyway), but they were $2 for the egg and $4 for the extra pork, on top of $15 ramen  it seemed a little steep. The ramen was TOTALLY fine without the extras. In fact, by "fine", I mean earth-shatteringly amazing. This ramen was also perfectly spicy but not mouth-burning. The noodles were really thin (angelhair diameter) but incredibly chewy and bouncy. Definitely thinner than I was expecting, but it was awesome. They were just a little hard to manipulate with chopsticks. So perfect though. I tried the broth from my friend's Classic ramen, and it was delicious but very smoky. A little too much smoke-factor for me, but definitely had the umami richness that my Modern had, and definitely did NOT have the spice that mine had (so if you're very sensitive to spice this could be perfect for you). In summary, I'm glad its finally cold enough to be noodle-soup-weather. Get to Ippudo asap. This is a great date spot, a great friend spot, a great friends-from-out-of-town spot, a great parents spot, etc etc. Just go. It's roomy inside, the service is ridiculously prompt, friendly and attentive (think people coming over 0.006 seconds after you spill a bit of food on the table to wipe it away with your old napkin and give you an old one), etc. The complimentary roasted barley tea (I think that was the variety) at the end of the meal was a nice touch. Small complaints: -Why don't they allow you to take your leftovers home? This struck me as weird especially since the ramen portion is HUGE and had I been able to, I would have brought half home. -The prices are pretty high, but I guess it is the best ramen in nyc (supposedly. But I'm in no position to argue this, nor do I want to).
