Honestly, I'm not sure I get what all the hype is about. Out of all the ramen places I've been to in NYC, Ippudo, while not bad, easily falls to the bottom of the list. Before, I go into the food, a huge part of my problem with Ippudo was with the ambiance. Now, I knew that Ippudo, one of the trendiest and busiest restaurants in the city, wasn't going to be the kind of place where my friend and I could have a quiet heart-to-heart. But what I didn't expect was that the music would be so loud that I wouldn't even be able to hear myself. As for the wait staff, service wasn't the issue (they were very good, actually). In a lot of Japanese restaurants, the waiters would yell "Welcome!" or "Irasshaimase!" whenever a new customer walked in. However in an extremely busy environment with a lot of people coming and going, it's actually kind of unpleasant to hear the staff yell every 5 minutes. On top of that, most of the staff are American and had really strong accents when speaking Japanese. That said, I personally felt that the food didn't really warrant the stressful environment. I had the Tori Ramen and my friend had the Shiromaru Hakata Classic. Each dish was well prepared and tasty but wasn't as delicious as the ones from some of the less expensive and more relaxed ramen joints in the city. I was also a little annoyed that eggs cost extra. In most ramen places, the soft boiled egg is an essential ingredient in the soup - to take that away and charge extra for it doesn't reflect the spirit of ramen! After all, ramen was originally a thrifty reinterpretation of Chinese noodle soup. All in all, Ippudo is a restaurant that has beautiful décor, good western-style service and tasty food. I'm just not sure that the ambiance is for me. Yuhe's Suggestions: - There are several things that I thought were rather well done: the tori (chicken) soup base, the bamboo shoots (nice and thick), and the chashu pork (slightly acidic). - Unfortunately, neither my friend nor I got the pork buns or the Akamaru Modern. I hear those are the standout dishes. - Come early! Ippudo opens at 11:00AM for lunch and 5:00PM for dinner - lines can get up to 2 hours if you come at peak times!
