It might be blasphemous of me to say this, but I thought that Ippudo NY was somewhat overrated. Maybe it had just been elevated too high in my mind, what with the almost 4000 reviews and all the raves and recommendation, but it was only okay in my mind. And at $14 for the basic ramen, it was just too expensive to justify regular visits. So, if this were any other regular-priced ramen place, I would have given it 4 stars. But because it's the vaunted Ippudo, I am lowering it to just 3. And i would add a half star for the fried chicken, rice, salad set too. I stopped by at 11am on a Monday right before the end of my visit to NYC. When I arrived at 10:50, there was already a line of people waiting. Luckily, when they opened the doors at 11, there was plenty of space and seating for all. As a singleton, I was seated at a large communal table that could seat 10. The service was extremely attentive. I was able to get my water immediately and order the Shiromaru Hakata Classic ($14) as well as the added mini lunch set side of Fried chicken (spicy) over rice and salad for $3. My ramen was described as "The original silky "Tonkotsu" (pork) soup noodles, topped with pork loin chashu, sesame kikurage mushrooms, menma, red pickled ginger, and scallions." Usually I order ramen without the red pickled ginger and the green onions, but I wanted the authentic Ippudo experience. The noodles were the thin, non-curly hakata style. They were cooked perfectly al dente and the regular amount was sufficient. The toppings were decent. The pork was somewhat tender, but really not the fattiest, most melt-in-your mouth tonkotsu that I have ever had in ramen. That distinction actually belongs to Dohatsuten of Palo Alto, surprisingly enough. The clear winner in this dish is the broth, which was really light and flavorful without being thick like many pork-based ramen broths become. The ginger was a nice addition to clear the richness of the flavor and clear the sinuses. But, is this worth $14? I don't think so. The portion size was not gigantic, and really it wasn't the best bowl of ramen I ever had. I did add the Nitamago - seasoned soft boiled egg for $2 and enjoyed that. But the egg was cold and had not been heated to the soup temperature yet. The yolk was definitely soft and runny and perfect. I was actually most impressed with the side of fried chicken over rice and the salad. I really liked the dressing on the salad greens. There was definitely a hint of wasabi in it as it kept clearing my nostrils in a pleasant way. Also, the fried chicken was delicious; crisp and juicy with just enough batter for a slight crunch. It was topped with a slightly sweet and spicy soy dressing as well as shavings of green onion. They gave me a ton of rice, which I wish now that I had used to sop up the remainders of the soup. It was actually really good sushi-grade quality rice, but I didn't want to fill up on it before the main event of the noodles. At $3, this addition was a steal and highly recommended. Would I return to Ippudo NY? Maybe. But I won't hold my breath on being blown away by the ramen.
