So I went to Ippudo and I managed to not jizz in my jeans upon the first time I slurped their ramen into my mouth.  Here's the incredible and true story of how I managed to contain my manly excitement. Being a guy who lives by himself in the East Village, one who is too lazy to cook, and who is a part of the Yelp community, constantly surrounded by self-proclaimed foodies, it is impossible for me to go about my meager existence in this beautiful yet tragically sadistic city without hearing about Ippudo once or twice a week.  This left me with two problems.  Problem number one: every self-indulgent hipster or yuppie and their mothers wanted to give the place a try, which meant there was always an incredibly long wait.  Supposedly a wait of up to an hour and a half was not uncommon.  One of my co-workers said he would put his name down and just go somewhere else for drinks and wait for them to call.  Problem number two: expectations were high. There was no way in hell I was going to wait an hour and a half to get a bowl of noodles.  I'd wait that long to meet Olivia Munn and get her autograph, but not for a bowl of noodles.  Actually I waited four hours to meet Olivia Munn and get her autograph at Midtown Comics.  While on my way back to the neighbourhood, and feeling a little hungry, I was thinking I should grab something to eat.  I happened to have been checking my facebook on my phone and one of my friends had just posted that she got into Ippudo by herself at 10:45.  This was Monday, and by the time I was a couple of blocks from Ippudo, it was 11:15.  Just me and my indignant self at 11:15 on a Monday night.  Perfect, let me try this. Alright, so I was seated right away.  Excellent.  I was happy I did not have to wait at all.  I was given a seat at one of the big round tables to share with other people.  This was apparently dimsum style.  It brought back so many sweet memories of the time I lived in Flushing.  But the similarity stopped there.  Unlike all the other ramen shops in the East Village, Ippudo was spacious, dimly lit, and had swanky decor.  It was also very, very loud.  I had no idea why the entire staff was yelling every time a party was finally able to get seated.  It wasn't like they were the ones who just waited an hour and a half to finally get a bowl of noodles.  Maybe they were just happy for the customers.  "You finally got a seat!  Hooray!" On to the menu.  The Shiromaru Hakata Classic caught my eye for having pork loin and red pickled ginger.  Then I thought, would this singular bowl of noodles be enough?  I had better order another dish, too.  The Kurobuta Steak Ginger Sauce caught my eye as well for being grilled...  pork loin...  topped with a fried poach egg.  Yes I love pork loin. The Kurobuta Steak Ginger Sauce came out quickly enough.  It was pretty good, but nothing too memorable.  The grilled pork was tender for being grilled, and the "Ippudo ginger Japanese sauce" was savoury and added moisture to the dish.  The fried poach egg, however, wasn't really necessary and I thought it didn't really add anything to the dish.   A group of three NYU girls had sat down at my big round table between the time I ordered and the time my grilled pork dish came.  Somehow their food arrived before my second dish, the noodles, came.  As if that wasn't annoying enough, I also had to watch one of them hold her chopsticks about an inch from the ends that touched the food.  To add insult to injury, one of the girls asked me to take a picture of them with her Nikon, and proceeded to tell me how to operate her crappy DNothing.  Are you kidding me?  I know how to use a damn Nikon. But I digress.  On to my noodles.  I have to admit that the broth was the best ramen broth I had ever tasted in this city.  For me, the difference was in the aftertaste.  At each and every slurp of the broth, the savoury flavour lingered in my mouth and the sides of my tongue like Dolores O'Riordan lingered in my mind after watching my first Cranberries video.  The pork loin, especially delicious for having swam in that broth, was so tender, it was ready to melt on my tongue and slide down the underbelly of my mouth as soon as I took a bite.  As for the noodles themselves, they were different from other ramen shops in the neighbourhood in that they were more uniform, and they were also a bit on the mushy side.  I actually prefer noodles that are not uniform, but that's just me. Yes, I agree Ippudo is the best ramen shop in this city.  But no, I did not have a gastronomical orgasm upon eating their ramen.  So there you have it.
