Once she had been initiated into the wonders that is ramen in NYC, one of my friends from Boston had been reminding me continuously since last February that we had, HAD, HAD to get ramen immediately once she came into the CIty in August. She would reiterated the dearth of available quality ramen in Boston. And almost daily, she would text me with one word: "RAMEN! (ok I'm exaggerating about the frequency). Having already went to Totto Ramen, we just had to visit the other NYC ramen institution: Ippudo. Ippudo was my first ramen experience in NYC back last September, and with the long gap in between, I had forgotten how it compared to the hype and wait time. My impressions from those first visits was that even though the ramen was top notch, I've had better for cheaper in LA (Daikokuya) and even, quite possibly, in NYC (Totto, Minca, Jin). We arrived 10 minutes before opening time for lunch on a Friday to put my impressions to the test. Now, I have regularly had to wait 1-2 hours for ramen at Ippudo. On busy days, the line already starts growing in front of the store 15 minutes before dinner time. The longest I've been quoted for has been 2-3 hours for a party of 6 on a Saturday at 7PM. Luckily for us that morning, we were one of the first people in line. If you really want to try Ippudo and you are on a schedule, coming before noon for lunch is the best way to get in without a wait. The food itself is great. The pork buns (2 for $10) are a must-get for first time visitors to Ippudo. More traditional than Momofuku's pork buns, the meat is less fatty yet still tender and complimented by the sauce. As for ramen, I advise first time visitors to start off with either Akamaru Modern ($14) or Shiromaru Hakata Classic ($14). The Classic is a great execution of tonkotsu ramen and rightly one of the best in the City. The Modern has a slight twist with the incorporation of miso paste and garlic oil. From  there you can explore other Ippudo options like the Wasabi Shoryu Ramen or spicy Karaka Men. Both aren't overwhelmingly spicy but well balanced with the rest of the flavors in the broth. The noodles are freshly made and perfectly cooked al dente. You can add additional toppings for a cost; I always get a hard-boiled egg or poached egg ($2). The hard-boiled egg is consistently executed so that the yolk is never overcooked and a perfect golden color. And if you know you will not full from your first bowl of ramen, save some of your broth and order kae-dama to get seconds on noodles. The service is great and you'll get a hearty Japanese greeting when you enter. Unlike many other ramen restaurants which tend towards being cramped ramen bars, Ippudo can accommodate larger groups (6-10 people) with the big booths, just expect to wait a while for them. However, after this visit, my friend and I agreed that Ippudo is not head and shoulders above the rest of the competition in NYC, which makes it hard to justify the wait times and slightly higher prices especially for egg since its included at other places. What ends up being a $20 bowl of ramen during dinner time can be had at half the price elsewhere (My friend seconds this opinion and says that Totto is better). A good place to take people from out of town but not a place that I would go to regularly. A solid ramen guaranteed every time. 4/5 stars.
