The idea of paying in excess of $10 for "Noodle Soup" doesn't really entice my taste buds.  Of course, paying north of $20 for a large Margherita Pizza made with either Fresh / Buffalo Mozzarella is also deemed as insane, yet I do it anyway.  Be that as it may, not having the pleasure of dining at Ippudo NY (after having eaten at other ramen notables as Momofuku Noodle Bar, Men Kui Tei, and Menchanko Tei), is comparable to saying you've had the best sushi in NY, without having gone to either Sushi Yasuda or Masa.  With that in mind, I ventured off to Ippudo NY on one fine Sunday afternoon. Arriving at the Ippudo was a sight in its own right.  It was evident that despite it being 2:30pm, there was already a wait for the table.  I promptly entered the restaurant and requested a table for two.  The host, Pierre, stated that it would be a 45 minute wait.  I proceeded to put my name down and headed straight to Pommes Frites during the 45 minute wait time (see Pommes Frites review)... 30 minutes later... I returned to Ippudo and was immediately seated after checking in with Pierre... The Ambiance...  Is best described as sleek with a modern Japanese twist.  The first notable eye catching display of the restaurant is the wall immediately behind the bar.  The wall is decorated with various ramen noodle bowls from different areas and time frame in Japan.  Additionally, the restaurant area has wall décor ranging from Japanese writing, black and red panels, as well as strategically positioned fluorescent lighting.  Lastly, the open kitchen provides a first hand sight into the ramen bowl assembly process.  It is clear, that the management company in charge of Ippudo spared no expense in making this establishment as "date friendly" as possible, while eliminating the common "hole in the wall" stereotype when it comes to noodle shops. The Service:  Was comparable and understanding to any amendatory requests of a particular dish.  I found that our waiter paid special attention to our requests when ordering and was prompt when requesting extra water or tea.  The turnover time is more favorable than that of any other noodle soup restaurant.  Ippudo provides a relaxing atmosphere that's laid back, which omits the feeling of a conveyor belt operation.  Our meal time at Ippudo lasted about an hour, at any other noodle shop, 15 - 20 minutes at most. The Food... Appetizer: Fried Shrimp w/ Spicy Mayo ($12) - 5 Extra Large Shrimp are Tempura Battered, then Deep Fried and topped with a Mild Spicy Mayo.  The Shrimp are served over a Mixed Green Salad with Balsamic Vinegar.  At first bite, the richness of the dish was evident in that the golden fried texture of the shrimp works harmoniously with the velvety spicy mayo.  The mixed green salad provided the acidity and texture required to balance out the heaviness of the shrimp and spicy mayo. Ramen Courses: Miso Ramen ($12) - Ramen Noodles in a thick broth, served with Berkshire Pork Cha Shu.  The only nod against this application is the lack of content served for the price paid!  The bowl contained two 1/4 ounce slices of Bershire Pork and at most 3 ounces of ramen noodle.  Despite the food contents of the bowl, the taste of the broth and noodles are best described as remarkable!  The ramen noodle possessed an overwhelmingly fresh taste, that was greatly aided by the lightly salted / creaminess of the pork broth.  Granted, I had to request a Kae-Dama (extra noodle serving).  Nevertheless, the taste of the noodle itself is incomparable to any other ramen establishment I've had the pleasure of dining at. Shoyu Ramen ($12) - Ramen Noodle in a Soy Sauce flavored borth, served with Berkshire Pork Cha Shu.  The application of this dish is similar to the Miso Ramen with respects to the contents.  The ramen used in the Shoyu application was that of a finer coarse ramen noodle (similar to the egg noodles found in Chinese noodle shops).  The texture of the noodle was well balanced with the darker and saltier broth.  One nod against the application would be that the soy sauce flavored ramen was a bit too salty and overwhelmed the semi-delicate texture of the fresh ramen.  Of course, the choice by the chef to use this particular broth with the ramen was of perfect pairing, as the ramen used in the Miso application would've been overwhelmed by the saltiness in the Soy Sauce Broth. The overall impression of Ippudo was that of applause and appreciation.  For starters, Ippudo reinforces the notion that it's patronage understands the difference between fresh and processed ramen.  In addition, the extra step Ippudo takes in properly matching the correct broth and noodle allows for a consumer to appreciate how the basic concept of "paying attention to detail" can render such a highly acclaimed product.
