n. The broth was thick and rich and full of porky-flavored goodness.  The ramen was on the thin side, but not overcooked to mushiness. It had a pleasing bite to it - al dente, I guess.  I splurged and had kakuni added to mine.  I figured that if I didn't like the ramen, I wouldn't want to come back just to have another $13 bowl of ramen with pork belly in it...  The kakuni was a good balance of pork and fattiness.  I liked the ball of yuzu kosho (yuzu pepper paste) that melted away into my broth. And, although the broth may have been a touch on the salty side, I did try to finish it all.  It was THAT GOOD. Love the toasted sesame grinders on the table.  Adds a yummy nuttiness to your ramen.  I may have to get myself one at home and do that instead of sesame oil from now on! Dessert options are limited - green tea brulee or sweet tofu.  We passed and went to Cha-an instead.
