Well, a little bit fancy for my tastes, but maybe that's just the NY way of doing good ramen. They have some good appetizers.  Like most places, it seems, it's a combination of izakaya and ramenya.  While most places seem to fall pretty flat trying to do both, Ippudo shines on both accounts.  The buns were delicious.  The seasoning in the buns was quite memorable, as opposed to just throwing in some hoisin and scallions.  And the crunchy asparagus pork maki (I had to just try this) was the tops.  Crunchy, but not overly breaded (so it didn't get soggy after 5 minutes like tempura), and balanced flavors. Oh, but the ramen.  I'm not a fan of the skinny noodles, but they stick to their hakata roots with the shiromaru: tonkotsu broth and thin noodles.  One sip, and I put this place in my top 5 or 6 in this country.  Though, it was a tad bit salty for my taste.  The akamaru adds some of their special miso, which adds some richness to the broth, but, surprisingly, wasn't quite as salty.  I'd probably get that next time. Oh, and this might be the best nitamago I've had in this country.  It was a bit well done on the outside, but it was still slightly runny on the inside.  While I wouldn't give up tasty soup for a perfectly done egg, it adds the wow factor for me, since it shows they're willing to put in the extra work.
