I had to come here on three separate occasions before I figured out how you actually get seated at this restaurant.  It's actually quite simple - come early (like 6pm) and put your name down.  They'll give you a wait time estimate (on the order of 1-2 hours) but you can pretty much ignore it.  It seems like the restaurant's policy is to let you come back at whatever time you like - even if your name was called 45 minutes ago! Now that said, the waiting experience can be fun.  Sure the bar area is ridiculously crowded at all times and you likely won't be able to sit down, but the edamame (served with soy salt) makes for delicious bar food, and the cocktails they have are very cool.  I strongly recommend the grapefruit juice with shochu, though I think half the fun was juicing my own grapefruit, and that wouldn't have been possible at the crowded bar (I ordered mine when we sat down). When we finally got past the hostess into the restaurant, I was shocked by the mammoth size of the place.  There's really a hell of a lot of space, and the environment is truly authentic Japanese - down to the windowed cooking area, communal tables, and constant shouting by the waiters to welcome EVERY party that gets seated.  Honestly, it's a loud place, and it is NOT romantic, which was actually perfect for my catching-up dinner... but I digress.  Just don't expect to get any real conversation in at this place. At first we thought the menu was laid out like tapas because there are so many appetizers and so relatively few entree/ramen options.  Wrong.  Coming to Ippudo and not ordering a ramen soup entree (~$14) runs against the grain here.  However I would definitely recommend getting 1-1.5 appetizers per person in addition.  Share them - they're amazing! We had the breaded tuna, which was out of this world and definitely my favorite.  We also had the hirata buns, which have a very unique texture and were basically mini chicken sandwiches.  The hirata chicken wings were delicious as well - the meat is very tender and comes right apart in your mouth. And finally the ramen.  I had the akamaru modern.  Delicious.  Especially the meat, which, like all the meat there, is ridiculously tender.  The broth was very rich and looked to have some cream in it, which scared me as a lactard.  You definitely don't need to heed their suggested add-ins, and they give you plenty of noodles so you probably don't need to save the broth for a refill of noodles ($2). In the end we had each spent ~$55.  I guess it all adds up!  It was worth it, definitely, but the myriad inconveniences bring Ippudo down to 4 stars.  I certainly will be coming back, but not soon or frequently.
