Having had almost no experience with ramen that didn't come bone-dry in plastic pouches, Ippudo was an eye-opener. The wait was over an hour and a half, having put a 8-person party on the list at around 7 pm on a Saturday. The lighting is dark and the decor is stylish, though thankfully the tables themselves are well-lit, and our booth looked out on the noodle bar and the kitchen. The tattooed, slinky-dressed maitre'd announced our entrance into the restaurant proper with a loud Japanese welcome, to which every waiter within earshot responded with a vague yell. A bit corny, but cute, nonetheless. Ironic, too, noting that everyone involved in this ritual was decidedly non-Asian, and our group was a group of Asians who knew perhaps 8 Japanese phrases between the lot of us. I ordered the Akamaru Modern (ramen) and Hirata Buns (pork), with Hotate Ponzu (scallops) and Shiromaru Hakata Classic (ramen) orders rounding out the rest of the table. The buns were very flavorful (a bit oversalted, in my opinion), and the ramen came in a large funnel-shaped bowl, topped with little piles of various sauce ingredients. Once you've muddled the sauce arrangement into a steaming pool of milky, creamy goodness, you're ready to eat. The noodles are unlike any Asian noodles I've ever had: barely thicker than angel hair pasta, holds flavor superbly, and with a substantial bite that'd make any al dente stickler proud. The ramen comes with a large soup spoon for slurping the soup as you eat the noodles, but for those with big appetites, go light on the soup-slurping at first, since having a healthy amount of remaining soup is required for ordering the $2 "Kae-dama" noodle refill. For a place that has the ambience of a good, slightly hipster East Village restaurant, the food quality to back it up, and a primetime wait of almost two hours, $16 for a double-helping of one of their most popular ramen bowls is a great value.
