Food:  Ippudo serves up a delicious bowl of ramen.  They serve up a number of varieties of soup (a basic soup, salt flavor, miso flavor etc.) combined with various toppings (pork chashu, poached egg, ginger etc.) and everything just works together. The soup is flavorful, the entire dish looks and smells great, but most importantly, the noodle itself is fantastic -- most people think of ramen as the dried packaged stuff, but real ramen is thinner the package stuff with great slightly elastic (in the best way, not chewy, but al dente-ish) texture. You have the option to buy some extra toppings for $2-$4, and you can also order additional noodles for $2.  The extra toppings are probably unnecessary because there is lots of flavor in the basic combinations, but the noodles may be necessary if you're feeling particularly hungry.   I don't bother with the appetizers or the dessert (because the ramen is filling enough) and because ramen is the obvious star. Price:  $13-$14 for a bowl of ramen.  If you're particularly hungry, pay $2 to get extra noodles.  You can definitely get out of here for $20 (tax and tip included) and feel completely satisfied. Service:  The wait is notoriously long if you come at around 1pm, and you can expect to wait over an hour.  Come here for an earlier brunch (11:30am) or for an early dinner (5:30pm) and you will be seated in about 15 minutes. Ambience:  This place is loud.  The servers yell all the time, so you will find your conversations cut short by bursts of Japanese.  It is louder or quieter depending on where you sit, but since you can't control where you sit, just be ready for some noise.  If you have a group of 4 or more, you may get a booth away from the kitchen which is more comfortable.  If you have just 2 or 3, you may be seated at a bar, or share a large round table, both of which are closer to the kitchen and louder.
