Ippudo is a wonderful establishment with some of the best ramen dishes in the city.  The decor of the restaurant is vibrant with kanji letters, ramen bowls on the walls and an open kitchen that shows all the magic in progress.  You get to experience all of this after a wait of no less than half an hour no matter the day you go.  The most recent trip was this past Wednesday where we entered the queue at 7pm and did not sit down to order until 830pm.  They do not take reservations. For appetizers, you have to get the Hirata Buns with pork.  The flavor of the pork is reminiscent to Chinese Char Siu and it is served with some of their own spicy sauce on steamed buns which I can only imagine what eating a cloud tastes like.  For the main course I almost always go for the Shiromaru Hakata Classic with added Kakuni.  It is a pork broth and it is amazing.  When I eat Chinese noodle soup, I usually finish the noodles and the wontons or fish balls or whatever I order with my noodles and call it a meal.  When eating ramen from Ippudo, I drink as much broth as I can with a spoon and I have to stop myself from lifting the bowl to my lips and slurping the last one or two gulps in the bowl.  It is THAT good.  The main garnish in the dish is the pork loin and even though it is very tasty, I need to add Kakuni or fatty pork belly.  They prepare it with a marinade that gives it a very unique smoky flavor and it is cooked just right so that it is firm enough to stay in one piece but is still tender enough that it falls apart once you bite into it.  My secondary choice is the Karaka Miso Ramen which I get when I need a spicy fix.  Basically, you cannot go wrong with any of their ramens. I would probably give Ippudo five stars if it was not for the awful wait everytime I go there.  Even if they would only take reservations for the day of and only starting at 4pm.  At least then I would only have myself to blame for not planning ahead to secure that reservation.  As things stand, I feel screwed over before I even get there.  If you are not pressed for time, Ippudo is a must.
