I brought a friend here to eat some longevity noodles for her birthday.  There were only two of us, and this particular friend does not have the propensity for gluttony that most of my other friends do, which means that she doesn't let me order half the menu like I want to. We started out with two shochu cocktails: I ordered the "shochu with fresh grapefruit" and she ordered the "green tea high".  The first arrived in two parts: a highball glass filled almost to the top with shochu, and a half a grapefruit with a citrus juicer.  My first thought was "whoa, is that glass really full of shochu? what a bargain!" Then, the waitress put the drinks down and started to walk away, and i stopped her, asking "Wait, I have to squeeze my own grapefruit?" She gave me a cheerful "Yup!" and hurried off.   I squeezed enough juice to fill my shochu glass the rest of the way, and took one sip, and promptly realized that there was probably about an inch of shochu, and the rest was water. Not so much the bargain I thought it was.   The "green tea high" was weird....it just tasted like iced green tea with some vodka in it.  I would skip the cocktails and stick with beer or sake at this place. The pork buns were very good, but not as good as momofuku's, and mine had a huge glob of mayo on one side which was not the greatest.  The roasted shishito peppers with yuzu salt were terrific.  Nice and hot, and the yuzu salt gave it a very tasty zing.  The shrimp tempura was not too greasy, the shrimp were perfectly cooked, and they had the perfect amount of sauce. The ramen is DEFINITELY the star of the menu.  We got the Akamaru Modern with soft egg and bakudan on the side.  This is the first ramen that I have had in 10 years that has been able to make a dent in my two long-time faves: Rai Rai Ken and Menchancko Tei.  Even Momomofuki comes in at 3rd place, but Ippudo may have just blasted its way into 1st.  The broth is delicious, the noodles are fantastically chewy, the cabbage is al dente, and the egg is perfectly soft-cooked...but what really made this ramen for me was the bakudan, which definitely had the flavor of sichuan peppercorns, which I like to affectionately refer to as  "crack". I will be back for this ramen.  It involves the "crack," so I probably could not stay away if I tried.
